===Etymology===
{{zh-ref|Unger (1995)}} suggests that {{zh-l|深}} had Old Chinese initial *''n-'' because of {{zh-l|淰|tr=shěn}}'s phonetic component {{zh-l|念}}.

{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} reconstructs {{och-l|深|tr=*nhəm}} & proposes relations to {{cog|lus|hniam||to be low, to sink into (land)}}, {{cog|my|နိမ့်သေ|'''နိမ့်'''|low}}, {{cog|nmf|tr=kʰənim|t=to be humble}}, {{cog|bo|ནེམས་||sink a little, give way}}, which Schuessler traces to {{cog|tbq-pro|*nem||low}}, which STEDT in turn derives from {{cog|sit-pro|*s-n(i/u)(ː)p/m ~ *r/s-nyap/m||pinch, squeeze; press, oppress; submerge, sink into, west, low, soft}}. If so, {{och-l|深|tr=*nhəm}} is from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|-}}.

Schuessler also notices {{och-l|深|tr=*nhəm}}'s similarity to {{och-l|沉|tr=*d-ləm}}, which he considers to be an {{w|Mainland Southeast Asia linguistic area|areal}} etymon.

Possibly cognate with {{zh-l|探}} and {{zh-l|揇}} (however, see there).

{{och-l|深|tr=*nhəms}}, "depth" (in ''{{w|Rites of Zhou}}'') & whence MC ''ɕiɪm<sup>H</sup>'', is nominal derivation with suffix *''-s'' (> departing tone).

{{och-l|淰|tr=*nhəmʔ}}, "be startled and flee {{n-g|(of fish)}}; i.e. to sink into the deep" (in ''{{w|Liji}}'') & whence Mandarin ''shěn'', is [[endoactive]] derivative with *''-ʔ'' (> rising tone).

